Kantara is example of a simple story being told in a brilliant way. The film revolves around tribal cultures and their clashes with govt officials, also talks about land acquisition, Bhoota Kola culture, etc.The intro was quite good but few minutes after the entry of the hero (who is also the director of this film) it stars getting boring.Some scenes even start to feel repetitive (some jump scare moments where the hero gets nightmares)You start to feel this is no more about Bhoota Kola and the film just revolves around ego fight between the hero Shiva and a DRFO police named Murali (played by Kishore KG)(Shiva vs Murali - a reference to GGVV? Maybe!)Climax was excellent and the ending (with the original Varaha Roopam song) was satisfying beyond words.The first and last 30 minutes were what engaged me. Rest felt like a dragged drama about village lifestyle.Highlights:1. Storytelling2. Sound Design3. Rishab's acting in the climaxDrawbacks:1. Deviations from the plot2. Boring in the middle3. Repetitive scenesVerdict:I say it's definitely a must watch film, but 9+ rating and calling it "Oscar worthy" is too much to praise as this movie is far from "perfect" but is undoubtedly one of the best in recent times.(3.5/5)Rating:Story: 3/5;
Screenplay & Direction: 3.5/5;
Production Values: 3/5;
Acting: 4.5/5;
Sound Design: 4.5/5;

